        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // Let the sorted array be a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Consider the partition where Class 1 takes the first n elements
        // and Class 2 takes the last n elements.
        //
        // This is not a valid partition because n can be even.
        // The problem states that each class must have an odd number of students.
        //
        // Let's re-read the problem carefully:
        // "assign each student to one of the 2 classes such that each class has odd number of students"
        // "The number of students in the classes may be equal or different, by your choice."
        //
        // Let the sizes of the two classes be S1 and S2.
        // S1 + S2 = 2n.
        // S1 must be odd, S2 must be odd.
        // If S1 is odd, then S2 = 2n - S1 must also be odd (even - odd = odd).
        //
        // The smallest possible odd size for a class is 1.
        // So, S1 >= 1, S2 >= 1.
        //
        // The median of an array of 2k+1 elements is the (k+1)-th element after sorting.
        // In 0-indexed terms, it's the element at index k = ( (2k+1) - 1 ) / 2.
        // So, for a class of size S, the median is at index (S-1)/2.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // If we want to minimize the difference between medians, we should try to make the medians close.
        //
        // Let's consider the specific case where both classes have size n.
        // This is only possible if n is odd.
        // If n is odd, then S1 = n and S2 = n are both odd.
        // In this case, the median of a class of size n is at index (n-1)/2.
        //
        // If we split the sorted array into two halves:
        // Class 1: a_0, ..., a_{n-1}
        // Class 2: a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}
        //
        // The median of Class 1 would be a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of Class 2 would be a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        //
        // This is a valid partition if n is odd.
        //
        // What if n is even? Then we cannot have two classes of size n.
        // We need S1 and S2 to be odd.
        // For example, if n=2 (total 4 students), S1, S2 must be odd.
        // Possible (S1, S2) pairs: (1, 3) or (3, 1).
        //
        // Let's consider the general case.
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference.
        //
        // It turns out that the optimal strategy is to take the middle two elements
        // of the sorted array, a_{n-1} and a_n, and make them the medians of the two classes.
        //
        // If we choose a_{n-1} as the median of the first class and a_n as the median of the second class,
        // we need to construct two classes around these medians.
        //
        // Class 1: median = a_{n-1}. This class must have an odd number of elements.
        // To make a_{n-1} the median, we need (n-1) elements smaller than or equal to a_{n-1}
        // and (n-1) elements larger than or equal to a_{n-1}.
        // The simplest way to do this is to take a_0, ..., a_{n-2} (n-1 elements)
        // and a_{n-1} itself, and then a_n, ..., a_{2n-2} (n-1 elements).
        // This would make a_{n-1} the median of a class of size 2(n-1)+1 = 2n-1.
        //
        // This is not quite right. The problem is simpler.
        //
        // The key insight for this type of problem is often that the optimal medians
        // will be adjacent elements in the sorted full array.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // Let's try to make the median of one class $M_1$ and the median of the other class $M_2$.
        //
        // If we pick $a_{n-1}$ as the median of the first class and $a_n$ as the median of the second class.
        //
