        // Class 2: $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$
        //
        // This is a partition into two classes of size $n$.
        // This is only valid if $n$ is odd.
        // If $n$ is odd, then the median of Class 1 (elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$) is $a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // The median of Class 2 (elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$) is $a_{n + (n-1)/2}$.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that the solution is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // Let's verify this.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // We want to find two sets $C_1$ and $C_2$ such that $|C_1|$ and $|C_2|$ are odd, $|C_1|+|C_2|=2n$.
        // Let $m_1$ be the median of $C_1$ and $m_2$ be the median of $C_2$.
        // We want to minimize $|m_1 - m_2|$.
        //
        // The smallest possible difference between any two elements in the sorted array is $a_i - a_{i-1}$.
        //
        // Consider the partition where Class 1 consists of $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and Class 2 consists of $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // This is a partition into two classes of size $n$.
        // This is only valid if $n$ is odd.
        // If $n$ is odd, then the median of the first class is $a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // The median of the second class is $a_{n + (n-1)/2}$.
        // The difference would be $a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        //
        // The example for n=1: [1, 1]. Sorted: [1, 1]. n=1 is odd.
        // Class 1: [1], median 1. Class 2: [1], median 1. Diff = 0.
        // Using the formula $a_n - a_{n-1}$: $a_1 - a_0 = 1 - 1 = 0$. This matches.
